  "prompt": "Is Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa an avatar?",
  "response": "Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa is regarded by many of his followers and devotees as a spiritual master and a saint, but whether he is considered an avatar is a matter of belief and interpretation among different sects and philosophical traditions within Hinduism. \n\nAn avatar is typically defined as a divine incarnation, where a deity manifests in a physical form. In Hindu tradition, figures like Lord Rama and Lord Krishna are commonly recognized as avatars of the god Vishnu. However, the assessment of whether Sri Ramakrishna fits into this category depends on individual beliefs, teachings, and spiritual perspectives.\n\nRamakrishna himself emphasized the idea of experiencing the divine through direct personal realization and advocated for the unity of all religions. His teachings and life inspired many, including notable figures like Swami Vivekananda, who spread his message globally. Some of his followers may view him as an avatar or a highly evolved spiritual being, while others might see him as a great saint or guru.\n\nUltimately, the perception of Sri Ramakrishna as an avatar or not is subjective and varies among different people and traditions.",
